  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "Here's an overview of the legal history of money laundering prohibitions:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Informal anti-money laundering (AML) practices existed in ancient civilizations\n- Formal legal prohibitions emerged more systematically in the 20th century\n\n2. United States Developments:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) - First comprehensive AML legislation\n- Established reporting requirements for financial institutions\n- Required documentation of cash transactions over $10,000\n\n3. International Milestones:\n- 1988 UN Vienna Convention against Illicit Drug Trafficking\n- First major international treaty addressing money laundering\n- Encouraged criminal prosecution of money laundering related to drug crimes\n\n4. Key Legislative Expansions:\n- Money Laundering Control Act (1986) - Made money laundering a federal crime\n- Anti-Drug Abuse Act (1988) - Further criminalized money laundering\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001) - Significantly expanded AML legal framework\n\n5. Global Regulatory Framework:\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- Created international standards for combating money laundering\n- Developed comprehensive recommendations for national legal systems\n\n6. Ongoing Evolution:\n- Continuous adaptation to emerging financial technologies\n- Increasing international cooperation and information sharing\n\nThis represents a broad overview of money laundering legal history.",
